TikTok hides unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok is censoring videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence or the outlawed Falun Gong religious group.
According to documents obtained by the publication, the owner of TikTok (ByteDance) uses the application to promote the goals of China’s foreign policy abroad.
The bulk of China’s policy violations fall under “hate speech.”
In each case, TikTok places objectionable posts in a context appropriate to the general rules, so that the actions of the social network do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticizing the socialist system of China falls under the general ban of "criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, the parliamentary system, etc.".
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tiananmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the “distortion of the history of China or other countries”.
The document also lists the banned names of twenty “foreign leaders or statesmen,” including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, U.S. Presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Posts from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may lead to the blocking of the user.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
Representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: “We are now using a localized approach for moderation, as well as attracting independent local specialists.”
Russian TikTok users have no specific restrictions on publication, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the Production Center.
Production Center is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Production Center" agrees with the representatives of the social network, but user materials can be placed without agreement, Bogdanov reports.
When asked whether TikTok can speak about politics or Putin, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he has seen such publications.
Roman Zaripov, founder of Our Digital, agrees with Bogdanov: "The basic rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: you can not post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on."
But under these rules, you can bring any content that does not like the moderators, says Zaripov.
Zaripov Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
By user agreement, TikTok can only be used by persons over 13 years of age.
The administrators of the social network check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
