The case was reviewed by human rights activists, journalists, scientists, teachers, doctors, and Orthodox priests.
Yulia Ustinova, the sister of Yulia Ustinova, told Interfax that her brother does not plan to speak at a rally on September 29 in the capital in support of the defendants in the “Moscow case”.
The supply of “sanctions” to Russia fell by 100 times
The government of the Russian Federation estimated that the supply of agricultural products and food to Russia from countries falling under the Russian food embargo has decreased more than 100 times since 2013.
According to the report sent to Russian President Vladimir Putin, in the first half of 2019, 31 thousand tons of products were imported from the sanction countries against 3 million 442.2 thousand tons for the same period of 2013, Interfax reports.
At the same time, the cost of imported products decreased to $226.5 million from $4 billion, 975.5 million, respectively.
We are talking about the supply of goods that did not fall under the embargo.
As indicated in the report, the fallen volumes of prohibited products were compensated by increasing imports from the CIS countries, Africa, South-East Asia, and Serbia.
Recall that at the end of August, the government extended until December 31, 2020 the validity of the rules for the destruction of agricultural products, raw materials and food, which are prohibited for import to Russia under counter-sanctions.
In the document posted on the official portal of legal information, it was noted that the validity of the rules has been extended for another year - from December 31, 2019 to December 31, 2020.
Initially, the decree on the abolition of the sanctions applied to products from the United States, the EU, Australia, Norway and Canada.
Later, from August 13, 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland, Liechtenstein joined this list, from January 1, 2016 - Ukraine.
The decree signed by Putin on the destruction of illegally imported into the country “sanctions” (products that fell under the food embargo, which Moscow imposed in response to the anti-Russian sanctions of the West) entered into force in 2015.
In turn, the government allowed the destruction of “sanctioned” food in any legal way.
As Western sanctions are maintained, Russia has also extended its retaliatory measures.
At the same time, this measure does not apply to products that citizens import for personal use.
The ban does not apply to the import of goods for personal consumption weighing up to 5 kilograms.
However, the head of the Council under the President of the Russian Federation for the development of civil society and human rights, Mikhail Fedotov, previously called the destruction of food products "simply immoral", and this, according to him, negatively affects the education of people.
Moreover, Rospotrebnadzor took the initiative to ban the destruction of edible food in early June.
After that, a similar recommendation to the government was made by the Human Rights Council under the President of the Russian Federation.
And Deputy Prime Minister Alexei Gordeev said that it is wrong to destroy food products, and you need to think about how you can use them for their intended purpose, assessing the quality.
The head of the company found guilty of tax evasion
By the judgment of the Leninsky District Court of Cheboksary, the director of LLC "Land and Law" Vyacheslav Morozov was found guilty of committing the crimes provided for in paragraph "b" of part 2 of Article 199 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (evading taxes from the organization by including in the tax declaration knowingly false information, committed in a particularly large amount) and part 2 of the Russian Federation.
This is reported by the press service of the Investigative Department of the TFR in Chuvashia.
From January 2008 to December 2009, Vyacheslav Morozov entered information on imperfect transactions in the tax accounting documents of LLC.
According to fictitious documents, the company incurred additional costs, and, therefore, the amount of taxes to be paid on value added and profit of the organization was reduced by 11.2 million rubles.
Vyacheslav Morozov was sentenced to 3.5 years of probation.
